'''Alexandra Munroe''' (born 1957) is a [[curator]] and historian of modern and [[contemporary art]] from Asia as well as a scholar of [[world art studies]] and transnational art history. 

Munroe organized the first retrospectives in America of several Asian-born artists, including [[Yayoi Kusama]], [[Yoko Ono]], [[Cai Guo-Qiang]], and [[Lee Ufan]].  Munroe's survey exhibition ''Japanese Art After 1945: Scream Against the Sky'' (1994<U+2013>95) initiated the academic and curatorial field of postwar Japanese art history in the United States.<ref>Cotter, Holland.  ''The New York Times''.  September 16, 1994.  [http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/16/arts/art-review-japan-s-avant-garde-makes-its-own-points.html "Japan<U+2019>s Avant-garde Makes Its Own Points.<U+201D>]</ref><ref >Joselit, David.  <U+201C>Artforum.<U+201D> May, 2013.  <U+201C>Categorical Measures: Exhibiting the Global.<U+201D></ref>

In 2006, Munroe was appointed the Senior Curator of Asian Art at the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York.  It was the first curatorial post of its kind in an international art museum devoted to modern and contemporary art.<ref>Scarlet Cheng. ''Art Ltd. Magazine''.  August 2008.  "Pacific Overtures: Influential Curators of Asian Art<U+201D>. [http://www.artltdmag.com/index.php?subaction=showfull&id=1219169363&archive=&start_from=&ucat=28&]</ref><ref>Vogel, Carol.  ''The New York Times''.  January 20, 2006.  "A Titian Travels to Washington / Guggenheim Curator<U+201D>. [http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/16/arts/art-review-japan-s-avant-garde-makes-its-own-points.html]</ref>

==Education and travels==
Munroe was born in New York City and raised in Mexico and Japan. She attended [[Brown University]] for two years and later received a bachelor of arts in Japanese Language and Culture from [[Sophia University]] (<U+4E0A><U+667A><U+5927><U+5B66>) in Tokyo in 1982. She was awarded a masters degree in art history from the [[New York University Institute of Fine Arts]], and in 2004, a Ph.D. in history from [[New York University]]. She studied under Harry Harootunian and wrote her thesis on postwar Japanese art and politics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/42586/Alexandra-Munroe-Named-First-Samsung-Senior-Curator-of-Asian-Art-at-the-Guggenheim |title= Alexandra Munroe Named First Samsung Senior Curator of Asian Art at the Guggenheim|work= Art Daily Online Magazine}}</ref>

Prior to her academic training, Munroe served as a resident lay disciple at Yotokuin, a subtemple of [[Daitokuji]] (<U+5927><U+5FB3><U+5BFA>) monastic compound in Kyoto, a historic center of [[Rinzai Zen]] from 1977 to 1980. She practiced [[chanoyu]] with masters of the [[Urasenke]] (<U+88CF><U+5343><U+5BB6>) school of tea and shimai with a master in the H<U+014D>sh<U+014D> (<U+5B9D><U+751F>) school of Noh theater. Munroe is fluent in Japanese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/42586/Alexandra-Munroe-Named-First-Samsung-Senior-Curator-of-Asian-Art-at-the-Guggenheim |title= Alexandra Munroe Named First Samsung Senior Curator of Asian Art at the Guggenheim|work= Art Daily Online Magazine}}</ref>

==Curatorial work and scholarship==
Munroe's survey exhibition ''Japanese Art After 1945: Scream Against the Sky'' (1994<U+2013>95) initiated the academic and curatorial field of postwar Japanese art history in the United States.<ref>Cotter, Holland.  ''The New York Times''.  September 16, 1994.  [http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/16/arts/art-review-japan-s-avant-garde-makes-its-own-points.html "Japan<U+2019>s Avant-garde Makes Its Own Points.<U+201D>]</ref><ref >Joselit, David.  <U+201C>Artforum.<U+201D> May, 2013.  <U+201C>Categorical Measures: Exhibiting the Global.<U+201D></ref>  Munroe organized the first retrospectives in America of several Asian-born artists, including ''Yayoi Kusama: A Retrospective'' (Center for International Contemporary Arts, New York, 1989); ''YES Yoko Ono'' ([[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society Gallery]], New York, 2000; traveled to 13 venues in U.S., Canada, Japan, and Korea through 2003); ''Cai Guo Qiang: I Want to Believe'' (Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, 2008); and ''Lee Ufan: Marking Infinity'' (Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, 2011).''The Third Mind: American Artists Contemplate Asia, 1860<U+2013>1989'' (Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, 2009) was among the largest exhibitions of Asian influence on American culture to date and received the inaugural Chairman<U+2019>s Special Award of $1,000,000 from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/25865/Guggenheim-Foundation-Receives--1-Million-Chairman-s-Special-Award-From-NEH|title= Guggenheim Foundation Receives $1 Million Chairman<U+2019>s Special Award from the NEH|work=Art Daily Magazine Accessed April 2, 2015}}</ref>

==Museum career ==
As Samsung Senior Curator of Asian Art at the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], Munroe spearheads the museum<U+2019>s Asian Art Initiative, expanding the institution<U+2019>s mission to study, acquire, and exhibit art from beyond the Western world.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/about/staff-profiles/curators/alexandra-munroe |title= Guggenheim Museum Staff Profile|work=Alexandra Munroe Guggenheim Museum Staff Profile |accessdate= March 15, 2015}}</ref> In this role, she guides the Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation<U+2019>s exhibitions, acquisitions, and public programs relating to Asian art for its museums worldwide. As a member of the Curatorial Working Group for the Guggenheim Abu Dhabi, she helps shape the future museum<U+2019>s collection.<ref>Vogel, Carol.  ''The New York Times''.  September 16, 1994.  [http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/16/arts/art-review-japan-s-avant-garde-makes-its-own-points.html "Japan<U+2019>s Avant-garde Makes Its Own Points.<U+201D>]</ref> Munroe has also organized and maintains the Asian Art Council, an advisory group composed of global art curators. <ref> {{cite web|url= http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Western-eyes-pivot-to-South-East-Asia-30244030.html |title=Western Eyes Pivot to South East Asia|work=The Nation Accessed April 3, 2015}}</ref>

Under Munroe's direction, the Guggenheim launched The Robert H. N. Ho Family Foundation Chinese Art Initiative in 2013 with a $10 million grant to study, present, and acquire contemporary art from China.<ref>Vogel, Carol.  ''The New York Times''.  March 19, 2013.  "Guggenheim Gets Grant to Commission Chinese Art.<U+201D> [http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/20/arts/design/guggenheim-gets-grant-to-commission-chinese-art.html]</ref>

Prior to the Guggenheim, Munroe was an independent curator based in New York and Tokyo before, in 1998, becoming Director of [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society Gallery]], and later, Vice President of Arts and Culture at Japan Society, an American organization dedicated to cultural and policy exchange between Japan and the United States. During her seven-year tenure, the society<U+2019>s contemporary art programs grew in size and stature through such exhibitions as ''YES Yoko Ono'' (2000) and the Takashi Murakami<U+2013>curated ''Little Boy: The Arts of Japan<U+2019>s Exploding Subcultures'' (2005). Both shows set record attendance for the institution.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.japansociety.org/resources/content/9/7/8/documents/CentBook.97-112.pdf  |title=Japan Society Historical Resource |work=Japan Society Timeline Accessed March 21, 2015}}</ref>
Munroe also curated the society<U+2019>s first inter-Asia loan exhibition, ''Transmitting the Forms of Divinity: Early Buddhist Art from Korea and Japan'' (2003) that was co-organized by the Japan Society; Korea Society, New York; Gyeongju National Museum, Korea; and Nara National Museum, Japan.<ref>Melikian, Souren.  ''The New York Times''.  April 12, 2003.  [http://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/12/style/12iht-melik_ed3__0.html "EXHIBITION /NEW YORK : Buddhism and the meeting of cultures.<U+201D>]</ref><ref>Cotter, Holland.  ''The New York Times''.  December 28, 2003.  [http://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/28/arts/art-the-highs-the-art-and-artists-of-the-year-685372.html "ART: THE HIGHS; The Art and Artists Of the Year.<U+201D>]</ref>

== Awards and honors ==
Munroe's exhibitions and publications have been recognized by numerous awards.  The [[International Association of Art Critics]] (AICA-USA) has cited four of her exhibitions: ''YES YOKO ONO'' (First Prize, Best Museum Show Originating in New York, 2001),<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.japansociety.org/resources/content/9/7/8/documents/CentBook.97-112.pdf  |title= Japan Society Awards History |work= Japan Society Timeline, Page 12, Accessed March 20, 2015}}</ref> ''Little Boy: The Arts of Japan<U+2019>s Exploding Subculture'', shared with Takashi Murakami (First Prize, Best Thematic Museum Show in New York, 2006),<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.artnet.com/magazineus/news/artnetnews/artnetnews1-26-06.asp |title=''Art Net News'', January 26, 2006 |work= Artnet Magazine}}</ref>  ''Third Mind: American Artists Contemplate Asia, 1860<U+2013>1989'' (First Prize, Best Thematic Museum Show in New York, 2010),<ref>{{cite web|url= http://artforum.com/news/id=24422   |title=AICA Names Exhibitions of the Year |work= Artforum, December 17, 2009}}</ref> and ''Gutai: Splendid Playground'' (shared with Ming Tiampo, First Prize, Best Thematic Museum Show in New York, 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.aicausa.org/news/aica-usa-arts-awards-honor-excellence-in-art-criticism-and-curatorial-achie |title= AICA-USA ARTS AWARDS HONOR EXCELLENCE IN ART CRITICISM AND CURATORIAL ACHIEVEMENT |work= AICA Announcement April 8, 2014}}</ref>

In 2012, the [[American Alliance of Museums]] conferred an Honorable Mention in the Publications Competition on ''Lee Ufan: Marking Infinity''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/press-room/news/4764-news-from-the-publishing-and-digital-media-department |title= Award for Guggenheim Publication and More Archival Books Online|work= Guggenheim News From The Publishing and Digital Media Department July 27, 2012}}</ref> Likewise, in 2009, the Association of American Museum Curators awarded ''The Third Mind: American Artists Contemporary Asia, 1860<U+2013>1989'' an Honorable Mention for Outstanding Exhibition Catalogue.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.artcurators.org/resource/resmgr/outstanding_exhibition_catal.pdf?hhSearchTerms=%22Third+and+Mind+and+American+and+Artists+and+Contemporary+and+Asia%22 |title= Recipients of the Annual Award for OUTSTANDING EXHIBITION CATALOGUE|work= Association of Art Museum Curators, 2012}}</ref>

In 2009, the catalogue for ''Cai Guo-Qiang: I Want to Believe'' took First Place for 30th George Wittenborn Memorial Book Award, presented by the [[Art Libraries Society of North America]], and in 2008<U+2013>09, China Art Powers named the exhibition the Best Show in China.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.arlisna.org/about/awards-honors/awards-history/173-george-wittenborn-award-past-winners |title= George Wittenborn Award: Past Winners|work= Art Libraries Society of North America, 2012}}</ref> In 1996, the catalogue ''Japanese Art after 1945: Scream Against the Sky'' was a finalist for the Alfred H. Barr Jr. Award for Outstanding Scholarship in a Publication, awarded by the [[College Art Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.collegeart.org/awards/barrfinalists |title= Awards: Alfred H. Barr Jr. Award Finalists |work= College Art Association Finalists America Listing Accessed March 20, 2015}}</ref>

In addition, Munroe has been a member of [[Association of Art Museum Directors]] (AAMD) since 2001 and is a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/about/membership/roster.html?letter=R|title= The Council on Foreign Relations Membership List|work=Council on Foreign Relations}}</ref>

== Philanthropy and activism ==
In April 2011, Munroe organized the Guggenheim<U+2019>s petition among museums worldwide in support of Chinese dissident artist [[Ai Weiwei]] and his release from state custody. Supported by the [[International Council of Museums|International Council of Museums (ICOM)]], the [[Association_of_Art_Museum_Directors|American Association of Museum Directors (AAMD)]], and the [[PEN American Center]], the petition garnered over 145,000 signatures in the United States and abroad at change.org.<ref>Vogel, Carol.  ''The New York Times''.  April 8, 2011.  [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/08/museums-press-for-the-release-of-ai-weiwei/ "Museums Press for Release of Ai Weiwei<U+201D>] </ref>

Munroe is a member of the advisory boards of Asia Art Archive, Hong Kong;<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.aaa.org.hk/About/People/AdvisoryBoard |title=Asia Art Archive Advisory Board |work=Advisory Board Members Accessed March 18, 2015}}</ref> LEAP, Beijing; Jnanapravaha Mumbai; Rockbund Art Museum, Shanghai;<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rockbundartmuseum.org/en/page/detail/ab8cs |title=Rockbund Art Museum Advisory Board |work=Rockbund Board Listing Accessed March 18, 2015}}</ref> and Ullens Center for Contemporary Art, Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://ucca.org.cn/en/about/advisory-board/ |title=Ullens Center for Contemporary Art Advisory Board |work=Ullens Center for Contemporary Art Board Members Accessed March 18, 2015}}</ref> She also serves as a trustee of the Aspen Music Festival and School;<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.aspenmusicfestival.com/about/about-the-aspen-music-festival-and-school/governance/board-of-trustees/ |title=Aspen Music Festival and School Board of Trustees |work=Aspen Music School Governance Section Accessed March 20, 2015}}</ref> Institute of Fine Arts, New York University;<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/fineart/about/trustees.htm   |title=Institute of Fine Arts, New York University Trustees |work= NYU Trustees Listing Accessed March 20, 2015}}</ref> and the US-Japan Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://us-jf.org/about-the-foundation/board-and-staff/ |title= US-Japan Foundation Board |work= US-Japan Foundation Board and Staff Listing Accessed March 18, 2015}}</ref>

Munroe is a trustee of The Rosenkranz Foundation, dedicated to innovation in public policy, higher education, and the arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://rosenkranzfdn.org/alexandra-munroe/ |title=Rosenkranz Foundation Directors |work=Rosenkranz Foundation Website}}</ref> In 2006, she and her husband [[Robert Rosenkranz]] cofounded Intelligence Squared U.S., a public-policy debate forum.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://intelligencesquaredus.org/about |title=Intelligence Squared U.S. Foundation |work=Intelligence Squared U.S. Website}}</ref>
Her philanthropy also includes the AKM Fund at [[New York Community Trust]], which sponsors end-of-life and palliative care training at [[Yale University School of Medicine]] and [[Harvard University]]<U+2019>s [[Massachusetts General Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.alexandramunroe.com/about-alexandra-munroe/philanthropy/ |title= Alexandra Munroe Philanthropic Initiatives|work=Alexandra Munroe Website  Philanthropy Section Accessed March 20, 2015}}</ref>

